@zugz wrote:
```
What is the purpose of the TOX_CAPABILITY_BASIC flag?
What does it mean if it is set to false? I don't think we should
actually reserve flags for anything yet where we can't specify
exactly what it will mean, as is the case at least for the PGC flag.
Separately: perhaps it would make sense to reserve the first bit for
future expansion - if it's set, it means "ignore this bitmap, and look
instead at the successor method of specifying capabilities"
(whatever that turns out to be).
```

@zugz 
it's a define, not a flag:

this means no special capabilities, in other words clients that are older
and did not implement this feature yet

#define TOX_CAPABILITY_BASIC 0

perhaps it would make sense to reserve the first bit for
future expansion
-->
that is: TOX_CAPABILITY_NEXT_IMPLEMENTATION

* Friday, 2019-05-03 at 14:16 -0700 - Zoff <notifications@github.com>:

>@zugz
>it's a define, not a flag:

Sorry, it looks like I meant `TOX_CAPABILITY_CAPABILITIES`. What would 
it mean if a client sent us a capabilities packet with this flag unset?

What could make sense is to use this bit rather than the highest bit to 
deal with future expansion. So this lowest bit being set would mean 
"interpret this uint64_t as describing my capabilities", while leaving 
it unset would indicate that another (as yet undetermined) system for 
describing capabilities is being used instead.

But generally, I don't think we should add these capabilities packets 
while we have no use for them. As it is, it would be complicating the 
protocol for no benefit. It's good to have a protocal and implementation 
up our sleeve in case we find we want to use it one day, and forks can 
use it if they want to, but I don't see why we would want to merge it 
now.


About the code:

* Need to check length of data when handling PACKET_ID_CAPABILITIES.

* Now we process packets from a non-online peer rather than returning -1 
as before. Presumably this was an accident?

* Why are we no longer sending an online packet in response to an online 
packet? Are you sure that wasn't there for a reason?

commit.message: return toxcore_capabilities even for offline friends

handle error in send_online_packet

add comment of int64_t to int conversion
fix: ISO C restricts enumerator values to range of ‘int’
check for length of packet, ignore if not ok

change comments

add TOX_CAPABILITY_CAPABILITIES as new default

remove unused line

(in case of a future bug *mocking* reserved)
